               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18150215-58-person499">
                  ROBERT 
                  EDWARDS
               <interp inst="t18150215-58-person499" type="surname" value="EDWARDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150215-58-person499" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150215-58-person499" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18150215-58-viclabel342" type="occupation">green-grocer and fruiterer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18150215-58-victim498 t18150215-58-viclabel342"></join>, I live at 23 Lower Shadwell. On the 7th of February, about half past six in the morning; I left my coat on the horses back; I was going to load my cart, I went away from my horse a quarter of an hour and when I returned I missed my coat; I know no more unless to prove my property.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18150215-58-person500">
                  JOSEPH 
                  CAMPBELL
               <interp inst="t18150215-58-person500" type="surname" value="CAMPBELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150215-58-person500" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150215-58-person500" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker, I produce a great coat, the prisoner pledged it with me on the 7th of February, in the name of Nicholls, for four shillings.</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. It is mine, I have had it four or five years, I am sure it is mine; I have seen the prisoner, he is a <rs id="t18150215-58-deflabel343" type="occupation">journeyman barge builder</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18150215-58-defend496 t18150215-58-deflabel343"></join>.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. As I was going to my work I saw the great coat lay in the horse path, I picked it up, and took it home, and kept it at home untill I carried it to the pawnbrokers. I shewed it to a young man that is here.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18150215-58-person501">
                  THOMAS 
                  ATKINSON
               <interp inst="t18150215-58-person501" type="surname" value="ATKINSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150215-58-person501" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150215-58-person501" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner bring in the great coat on his arm, about eight o'clock in the morning, it had the appearance as if he had picked it up in the road.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18150215-58-verdict344" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18150215-58-verdict344" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>First Middlesex jury, before Mr. Justice Heath.</p>
